WEBVTT

00:00.418 --> 00:02.821
Hey everybody, welcome back to the Menlo Midweek Podcast.

00:02.861 --> 00:04.523
We are so glad to have you today.

00:04.824 --> 00:05.805
My name is Matt.

00:06.045 --> 00:06.926
And my name is Brett.

00:07.187 --> 00:09.049
And today we are your hosts.

00:09.289 --> 00:11.012
Talking about this past Sunday.

00:11.492 --> 00:11.913
This past Sunday.

00:12.474 --> 00:12.734
Big week.

00:13.014 --> 00:13.735
It was a big week.

00:13.775 --> 00:14.096
Yeah.

00:14.116 --> 00:16.839
For those of you who don't know, Brett is our director of NextGen.

00:16.939 --> 00:19.422
I feel like everybody knows probably you more than me.

00:19.823 --> 00:20.864
I don't know about that.

00:20.884 --> 00:22.366
The various circles you run in, man.

00:22.386 --> 00:23.468
You are all over the place.

00:23.488 --> 00:24.569
And you've been here how long now?

00:24.649 --> 00:26.251
I've been here 13 years.

00:26.451 --> 00:26.792
Bro.

00:26.832 --> 00:27.092
Yeah.

00:27.573 --> 00:28.434
Legend.

00:28.546 --> 00:29.527
legendary.

00:29.848 --> 00:33.152
Um, well, uh, it is great to have Brett on the podcast today.

00:33.252 --> 00:35.475
So, uh, we're going to talk about this past Sunday, Brett.

00:35.495 --> 00:35.895
Yeah.

00:35.915 --> 00:38.438
It was a student Sunday, student Sunday.

00:38.458 --> 00:52.115
Now I will say for me, having worked at the campus level and at the central level, I do notice, uh, this vibe that occurs with adults who are on campus and regularly serving in various capacities in the church.

00:52.716 --> 00:54.258
When we say,

00:54.818 --> 00:57.180
we're going to allow our students to like run a Sunday.

00:57.481 --> 01:03.907
There's like this sort of controlled chaos and like unease of like, okay, like we're letting the kids drive the car now.

01:04.447 --> 01:05.609
So what's it like for you?

01:06.029 --> 01:09.132
What do you, what stands out most to you for students Sunday across our campus?

01:09.152 --> 01:12.976
Like how does that, how does all of this coalesce and land on you as a leader?

01:13.476 --> 01:14.677
Yeah, that's a great question.

01:14.978 --> 01:23.506
You know, I think when we talk about students Sunday, there's been a kind of a wide range of what that has looked like or what that can look like.

01:23.618 --> 01:32.065
What I would I'll just say what I love about students and they how I kind of have approached and what I've loved about this year is when worship talked about student Sunday of here's what we're going to do.

01:32.106 --> 01:37.202
They were talking about what we want for this to be is a picture of.

01:37.250 --> 01:47.659
what can the church look like when it's not just like here's students running everything and then adults are on the side, but here's what it looks like when the church is all generations serving and leading and working together.

01:47.739 --> 02:02.972
And I think that's kind of what we ended up seeing at our campuses where you had students hosting alongside the AFP's or you had students in the band alongside adults or people greeting alongside other adults that it's not like a either or thing, but it's a where this church together.

02:03.613 --> 02:07.236
So as like from my seat, that's what I enjoy seeing is just like, okay,

02:07.216 --> 02:14.463
We actually are working together and this is a picture of who Menlo can be if we truly become like an intergenerational church.

02:14.784 --> 02:15.705
That's great.

02:15.725 --> 02:20.750
And I think for me when I see it, you know, I see how that participation is formational.

02:22.932 --> 02:30.580
I remember what it was like to be a high school student and there were spaces or things that I felt like I couldn't own because I wasn't invited or asked to do it.

02:31.000 --> 02:33.923
But when I was, I was like, hey, this is awesome.

02:34.043 --> 02:36.626
It's kind of like back to the car thing like,

02:36.994 --> 02:39.597
like someone flipping you the keys and saying like, hey, park my car.

02:39.617 --> 02:40.278
You're like, really?

02:40.298 --> 02:41.659
I get to do this.

02:42.200 --> 02:43.761
And like, there's just something fun about that.

02:44.282 --> 02:55.975
So my next question is, what do you see in adults that maybe they're processing or maybe even misunderstanding about the faith of Gen Z or Gen Alpha?

02:56.015 --> 02:57.316
What do you see in adults?

02:57.517 --> 03:02.482
Yeah, I think all of us have a natural tendency

03:02.658 --> 03:11.234
to think about when we think about students, we think about what it was like when we were a student, and to say what we went through is exactly what they're going through now.

03:11.735 --> 03:13.177
And yes, there are similarities.

03:14.339 --> 03:20.731
But what I see adults who are really connecting with the next generation, they're adults who are very curious.

03:21.092 --> 03:21.853
They ask questions.

03:21.873 --> 03:23.737
They try to understand what is happening.

03:24.298 --> 03:26.642
And they take time to actually learn like,

03:26.946 --> 03:28.989
Yeah, what is going on in a student's life?

03:29.049 --> 03:29.750
What are they asking?

03:29.770 --> 03:34.656
And I would say what I've noticed is that students' faith right now is they are very curious.

03:34.977 --> 03:36.278
Like they want to know more.

03:36.318 --> 03:38.161
They want to see a faith that is real.

03:38.501 --> 03:46.892
They want to have a safe space to wrestle with their questions, even if the answers aren't very clear or it's not as black and white.

03:46.932 --> 03:48.955
Because they're talking about these things in the school.

03:49.015 --> 03:50.036
Thanks to social media.

03:50.297 --> 03:53.120
You're constantly getting all sorts of answers for a lot of things.

03:53.160 --> 03:54.322
And so students are wondering,

03:55.042 --> 03:56.464
Where can I discuss these things?

03:56.524 --> 04:00.209
And if they don't have it in the church, they find it elsewhere.

04:00.429 --> 04:00.770
They do.

04:01.431 --> 04:03.974
And those resources are abundant as well, right?

04:03.994 --> 04:04.695
Yes, very much so.

04:05.316 --> 04:10.343
I mean, you know, in our generation, it was, oh, yeah, let's go to ask geez, you know.

04:10.363 --> 04:10.864
Get throwback.

04:10.884 --> 04:11.505
Yeah, I know.

04:11.545 --> 04:12.146
Really good throwback.

04:13.407 --> 04:14.309
Classic millennial move.

04:14.609 --> 04:15.410
And now,

04:15.522 --> 04:31.250
There are so many ways they are over resourced to be able to find answers and I mean, maybe it's a benefit sort of of the AI Bloom that we're seeing where questions and curiosities lead to more questions and more curiosities and

04:31.458 --> 04:45.800
It's a good diagnostic for the church to say like, okay, how are we orienting ourselves to be able to handle some of this, to be able to help internalize and metabolize some of the energy that they're bringing into this and respond accordingly in a way that's true and authentic.

04:46.240 --> 04:48.023
But I love what Phil said on Sunday.

04:48.043 --> 04:51.248
He was just like, hey, our students are not the church of tomorrow, they're the church of today.

04:51.288 --> 04:54.573
And that's exactly the present time that we're living in.

04:55.234 --> 05:00.562
Okay, so I want to get to a little bit of Phil's message here because I just thought it was good.

05:00.706 --> 05:13.361
He had mentioned, you know, we talked about the passage around Jacob, and Jacob and Esau, and Jacob wrestling with God, the only dude that we know who actually like had a, you know, prize fight against the divine, which I think is really interesting.

05:13.802 --> 05:14.262
And one.

05:14.302 --> 05:15.464
And one?

05:15.544 --> 05:17.046
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

05:17.066 --> 05:18.908
Yeah, he got something out of it for sure.

05:19.308 --> 05:23.694
Yeah, he had a permanent takeaway as well, which was interesting, but we'll get there.

05:24.855 --> 05:27.218
Phil had said, you know, faith grows in wrestling.

05:27.490 --> 05:28.151
not retreating.

05:28.732 --> 05:33.058
And I would just ask, you know, where do you see some of our students wrestling right now?

05:35.542 --> 05:46.738
I think, yeah, with faith questions, a lot of, I would say a lot of the wrestling questions that I will hear students ask are the same questions that we ask as adults.

05:47.010 --> 05:49.318
Like it's questions of, can I believe this?

05:49.398 --> 05:50.682
I'm seeing stuff in the news.

05:50.743 --> 05:51.826
I hear about Christians.

05:52.248 --> 05:57.746
And can I actually follow a God when I see Christians living in a way that doesn't seem to reflect the God that...

05:57.890 --> 06:00.132
I'm told about in church, so they're wrestling in that way.

06:00.172 --> 06:05.137
They're also wrestling with questions of identity and purpose of who am I?

06:05.317 --> 06:09.221
Because as a student, you're constantly being told, this is who you are.

06:09.261 --> 06:16.107
These are the classes that you need to take in order that you can get into that college to have that career.

06:16.167 --> 06:17.829
And those are the things that define you.

06:17.849 --> 06:21.633
They're looking for purpose of knowing like, do I matter?

06:21.653 --> 06:27.378
And so I think you see those restlings that are often also the same things we are too.

06:27.522 --> 06:32.567
But it just, again, it looks different based on the context that they're in right now.

06:32.587 --> 06:39.734
And I think a lot about the performative nature of the Bay Area, the scholar athletes, the academics that we have here.

06:40.075 --> 06:49.744
Again, incredible resources and privileges for students to be able to engage in various different ways, but all of those have a formational energy to them.

06:49.764 --> 06:50.445
Absolutely.

06:50.465 --> 06:55.250
And they change the dynamic of how they're defining themselves.

06:55.362 --> 07:19.122
sometimes it's you know what it's like to be a kid sometimes it's a while before you figure out who you are even in the college realm like you step into that and like you know legally you're an adult and but it doesn't feel that way right yeah yeah and it's I mean talking about the Bay Area the performative nature like I've had so many conversation with students who say I really want to make my faith a priority but

07:19.490 --> 07:21.192
I also have this tutor.

07:21.413 --> 07:22.875
I also have this sports team.

07:22.955 --> 07:24.176
I also have this play.

07:24.256 --> 07:26.139
I have these things that I have to do.

07:26.820 --> 07:31.186
And they, if I don't do those things, I can't be a part of them.

07:31.206 --> 07:48.028
Whereas faith, there's not really that like, if you don't do this now, sorry, you're out because we always want them to be welcomed here and feel like they belong, but they constantly are living in this tension and wrestling with how do I make time for the thing that I know I really want to, but that's not going to get me into college.

07:48.308 --> 07:48.529
Yeah.

07:48.909 --> 07:49.490
Yeah.

07:49.730 --> 08:07.993
And sometimes, I'm thinking back to Phil's message, he mentioned how we have RAM, random access memory for different aspects of our lives, and that sometimes, maybe it's too many tabs are open, too many things are happening, God crashes the system of our lives.

08:08.454 --> 08:17.906
And I've encountered many students, and I'm sure you have, where they're on the athletic track for school, and then they get an injury that changes everything.

08:18.306 --> 08:22.092
or they're testing into something and they fail miserably.

08:22.973 --> 08:29.764
And I mean, if that hasn't happened to you when you're young, it's likely that pain is out there for you somewhere into adulthood.

08:30.165 --> 08:40.141
And so I would just say, if you're young, how do we help students interpret that experience as mercy instead of failure?

08:41.182 --> 08:41.923
Yeah, great question.

08:42.004 --> 08:46.130
I think the first thing we always have to try to remember

08:46.306 --> 08:50.491
is that we need to affirm who they are in Christ first, no matter what.

08:50.931 --> 08:55.997
Because I think part of the reason why we crash so hard is because we're looking at those other things that define us.

08:56.417 --> 08:59.281
And when those things crash, we begin to wonder, who am I?

08:59.761 --> 09:11.314
And so if we are thoughtful around telling every single student, man, before you get that grade, before you get into that school, before you get whatever, you are somebody who is deeply loved by God.

09:11.522 --> 09:14.405
and just constantly letting that be what we say.

09:14.505 --> 09:16.728
I think that helps on the crashing end.

09:16.748 --> 09:19.932
Of course, when students are surrounded by other voices saying the same thing, it's hard.

09:21.013 --> 09:23.756
But that always has to be the first thing that we have to do.

09:24.697 --> 09:35.589
And then I think beyond that is you just take time to sit with students and to help them see that God is with them in this, I'm with you in this, and that's not gonna change it.

09:36.390 --> 09:39.634
We're in the season where you're naming the different things

09:39.714 --> 09:41.216
Things that might happen to students.

09:41.236 --> 09:43.619
We're in the college acceptance and rejection season.

09:43.940 --> 09:47.865
And this is something that when I moved to the Bay Area, I was shocked by.

09:48.105 --> 09:55.815
Because when I grew up in college or grew up in high school in East Tennessee, you would apply to a couple of schools and you'd probably get into one.

09:56.757 --> 09:59.660
Nowadays, some students are applying to 20 to 30 schools.

10:00.101 --> 10:03.826
And yes, you might get into a school, but every time you get a rejection,

10:04.162 --> 10:08.008
Even if it's not a school you want to go to, you begin to wonder what's wrong with me.

10:08.028 --> 10:09.490
And so you get to that crashing moment.

10:09.770 --> 10:12.254
It's like, how do we just walk alongside them and tell them?

10:12.274 --> 10:13.196
Yeah, that's great.

10:13.997 --> 10:14.698
This is who you are.

10:15.960 --> 10:16.040
Yep.

10:16.060 --> 10:19.525
And I do think that rejection can build resilience.

10:19.645 --> 10:20.066
Absolutely.

10:20.286 --> 10:33.426
But at the same time, if you don't have a core foundational principled nature on your own identity and how that connects back to the God who made you, it can feel really

10:33.634 --> 10:35.765
on mooring and devastating in a lot of ways.

10:35.845 --> 10:39.282
And so that's just a great point.

10:39.426 --> 10:40.708
across all of our campuses as well.

10:40.728 --> 10:45.895
We also celebrate a baptism, which is just a great next step of faith that we see people taking.

10:45.955 --> 10:49.540
So we had a big weekend, we had students Sunday, we had a great message, and we had baptisms.

10:49.880 --> 10:52.965
And I would just say, I saw some grown-ups get baptized.

10:53.005 --> 10:56.650
I've had the privilege of baptizing both grown-ups and students at Menlo.

10:56.670 --> 11:08.306
But I would just ask you, Brett, as a leader for students, and you've kind of got your hand on the pulse of all that, what do you think it does for students to see adults take a step of baptism?

11:08.706 --> 11:24.466
Yeah, I think one of the, this is some of the reasons why we have adults in students' lives as life group leaders is when you have an adult in a student's life, they get a little picture of this is what my life could be like in the future, or this is like, I could actually potentially follow Jesus as an adult.

11:24.486 --> 11:28.651
And I think it also communicates, hey, it's never too late to come to Jesus.

11:28.672 --> 11:33.778
And so when students get to see adults professing their faith, they're seeing somebody who's

11:33.922 --> 11:37.243
beyond them in years, whatever it may be, whether it's older or even just 10 years.

11:37.625 --> 11:40.402
And they see, okay, this is somebody that I can look up to.

11:40.482 --> 11:43.345
and potentially become for the next generation.

11:44.126 --> 11:54.678
I think even the students who are getting baptized, like at all of our campuses, we didn't have our middle school ministry meet at their normal time this week because we had them in the service to watch baptisms.

11:54.798 --> 11:59.042
And at Mountain View, we had three high school students get baptized at the 1130.

11:59.123 --> 12:01.165
And so the middle schoolers got to be in there.

12:01.205 --> 12:04.969
And one of those high schoolers was a life group leader for the middle schoolers.

12:05.329 --> 12:09.554
And so those middle school students got to see their leader profess their faith

12:09.826 --> 12:11.929
and say, I want to live my life to follow him.

12:11.949 --> 12:19.058
And so if you're a student and you're seeing somebody you look up to do that, I can't imagine it to do anything but make you more excited about following Jesus.

12:19.158 --> 12:19.439
Yeah.

12:20.160 --> 12:21.521
One generation blesses another.

12:22.222 --> 12:34.879
And I mean, again, just calling it back to my own teenage years, I can recall with great clarity the names of the adults that invested into my life, what they did for me, and how it made a difference.

12:35.239 --> 12:37.362
And to even see

12:37.634 --> 12:44.865
their growth and their trajectory is inspiring to me as a young person saying, we are never done growing.

12:45.686 --> 12:47.148
God has never done working on us.

12:47.609 --> 12:50.593
And I feel like baptisms are a great reminder of that.

12:51.134 --> 13:04.594
And in a way now as a believer with a couple years in, I feel when I see people take a step of faith in that regard, it reminds me of that own time in my life where I reconnected with what God was doing.

13:04.738 --> 13:07.542
But baptism, it's an uncommon act.

13:08.423 --> 13:11.246
We don't have a framework for it in the secular world.

13:11.707 --> 13:23.923
And I just think it's one of those things where because it's not a regular practice, because it is a sacred practice, it feels counter-cultural to students.

13:24.904 --> 13:31.793
How do you communicate with students when you're talking about what baptism is and why it matters for them?

13:31.973 --> 13:32.754
What do you say to them?

13:32.962 --> 13:39.333
Yeah, this is actually one of the big questions that students oftentimes have because they say, hey, I followed Jesus.

13:39.373 --> 13:40.815
So why should I get baptized?

13:41.336 --> 13:47.908
And part of what I'll talk to them about in that is that when we get baptized, like obviously we don't believe that baptism saves us.

13:48.769 --> 13:54.879
But it is a chance that you are kind of making it known that you are living your life to follow Jesus.

13:55.000 --> 13:56.402
And in a sense, when we're

13:56.610 --> 13:59.493
When we're getting baptized, we're throwing a party for you.

13:59.554 --> 14:06.282
And it's not just for you, but it's for the entire church to say, hey, you aren't just making this decision for yourself, but now you are a part of us.

14:06.382 --> 14:07.563
You are a part of this community.

14:07.583 --> 14:10.747
And we promise to be walking alongside of you to support you.

14:10.787 --> 14:17.335
Like we talk about a lot, the covenant community that like we are the people who want to be with you for the rest of your life.

14:17.355 --> 14:19.858
And so telling students that this isn't just a you thing.

14:20.034 --> 14:25.162
Um, like Jesus got baptized and Jesus said an example for us of this is how we get to do it.

14:25.182 --> 14:26.805
And now we get to go and do the same.

14:26.925 --> 14:34.778
And so when you share your story, you are not just, um, saying the one other, I've made this decision, but you're also blessing the community as well.

14:34.798 --> 14:36.661
And so kind of talking with them about that.

14:36.681 --> 14:44.934
Cause I would say more often, like, yeah, more often than not, I'm having conversations with students or saying, I'm not really sure if I want to do this.

14:45.014 --> 14:47.378
And typically it's, I, I'm not,

14:47.554 --> 14:54.003
sure I want to be in front of everybody because it's a little, yeah, if you're, if you're shy or if you're introverted, you're like, I don't want to do that.

14:54.344 --> 15:00.893
But it's like helping them understand that, no, this is a chance that we get to just celebrate and proclaim the good news to the larger church.

15:01.574 --> 15:13.410
And I would just say, if you're listening in your, you've got, you know, maybe you felt the call to be baptized before, or you wanted to take that step, but you've avoided it because of the public nature of it.

15:13.570 --> 15:16.114
I would just say that public

15:16.194 --> 15:22.663
moment for you is just a moment, but it can matter so much in the life of someone else, someone young or old.

15:22.983 --> 15:24.305
It could be a moment of inspiration.

15:24.545 --> 15:33.618
And when Jesus had that moment, I mean, it was sort of captured for all of us to see, but it inspired so many in the process.

15:33.898 --> 15:39.666
And what I love about the nature of baptism is that, especially for a young person, it

15:40.098 --> 15:41.781
removes that pressure to perform.

15:42.402 --> 15:46.088
You're there, but you're not actually there for you.

15:47.350 --> 15:49.413
You're there because God has done the work in you.

15:49.974 --> 15:52.478
And it wasn't anything that you had to achieve.

15:53.099 --> 15:54.541
It was something that was gifted to you.

15:55.964 --> 16:02.354
So I'm just saying, if you're listening and you're like, yeah, baptism feels cool, but I'm not ready to take that.

16:02.434 --> 16:05.784
We would love to talk to you about that because it makes a difference in so many lives.

16:06.025 --> 16:13.608
And I love that we've now started recording everybody's story before they get baptized, so that we both get to watch it and hear it together.

16:13.969 --> 16:15.794
But also it's a gift for

16:15.842 --> 16:22.369
the students or the people who get baptized, they get to go back and watch their story and be reminded of, this is why I made that decision.

16:22.789 --> 16:32.539
And I hear every single time we do a baptism sermon, people come up to me afterwards and just say, well, one, the person getting baptized says how grateful they were that they actually made this decision.

16:32.900 --> 16:37.825
And then two people in the congregation will come up and say, this was absolutely my favorite Sunday of the year.

16:38.085 --> 16:40.227
Yeah, yep, yep.

16:40.728 --> 16:42.770
Filmmaker, Cameron Crow,

16:42.914 --> 16:47.820
He, I watch an interview with him once, and he said he doesn't journal at all.

16:47.940 --> 16:49.122
He never writes down his thoughts.

16:49.722 --> 16:51.184
He makes mixtapes.

16:51.645 --> 16:52.546
Literally.

16:52.986 --> 16:57.412
Yes, like of the songs that are playing at different seasons in his life.

16:57.752 --> 17:01.917
And he says, every once in a while, like I'll pop in an old mixtape from a few years ago.

17:02.558 --> 17:04.540
He's like, and it is just as good as a diary.

17:04.660 --> 17:08.926
He's like, I remember everything that was happening to me and through me in that season.

17:09.426 --> 17:12.530
And I would just say like baptism and that moment

17:12.642 --> 17:14.204
like that's your mixtape.

17:14.224 --> 17:20.229
Yeah, like that's God saying to you like, hey, here's what I did in and through you in this season of life.

17:20.330 --> 17:21.611
And I don't want you to forget that.

17:21.911 --> 17:25.054
And that, I mean, it's true for me, it's true for so many.

17:25.695 --> 17:27.236
And that just resonates with me.

17:27.296 --> 17:33.222
So one of the other things we talked about is Jacob in the sermon.

17:33.442 --> 17:35.965
And he wrestles with God.

17:36.005 --> 17:41.330
But before he got his new name, he had to say his old one.

17:41.474 --> 17:52.366
And I think in a generation that is constantly curating an identity, how do we help students wrestle honestly with who they are in God?

17:54.007 --> 17:56.550
Yeah, in some ways, I think this goes back to what I was saying earlier.

17:56.590 --> 18:07.602
If we just have to be constant repeaters first of who they are, like constantly saying that before we ask them questions about how did they do or anything like that, just talks to them about

18:07.714 --> 18:10.037
how they've been created, who God says they are.

18:10.737 --> 18:22.871
Because when we start with that foundation, it gives them the freedom to kind of wrestle, because I think sometimes the reason they might be afraid to wrestle is they're afraid of, if I speak up about this, is that going to change somebody's perspective of me?

18:22.891 --> 18:28.738
So if we start with saying who you are and you're going to be loved and cared for no matter what, it creates a safe space for that.

18:29.799 --> 18:32.082
One of the things we do at

18:32.386 --> 18:40.679
In some of our high school ministries, we do this at Mountain Dew every week, which you know is we have a question box where students can put in any question they want about anything.

18:41.180 --> 18:44.566
And we will take it out and we will talk about that question for three to five minutes.

18:44.966 --> 18:49.874
And why we do that is because at the very beginning, I'll say we do this.

18:49.986 --> 19:02.799
so that because we want the church to be a safe space where you can wrestle with anything, where there is nothing that you say, nothing that you ask, that'll change the way we view you, because we believe every single person is created in the image of God.

19:02.919 --> 19:05.101
And so because of that, feel free to ask questions.

19:05.162 --> 19:07.264
God's not afraid of your questions, so let's wrestle together.

19:07.664 --> 19:14.271
So I think it's just creating that space constantly saying, you are safe, you are loved, nothing will change that.

19:15.132 --> 19:15.852
And letting it happen.

19:16.533 --> 19:17.394
Yeah, that's good.

19:17.538 --> 19:19.844
And it's, I mean, it models the pattern of Jesus.

19:20.125 --> 19:23.854
Jesus was not afraid of questions or confrontation in that regard.

19:24.135 --> 19:30.792
And the way he directed and taught people is that he sat with them in the process and listened intently and walked alongside them.

19:31.052 --> 19:34.802
And in an age where

19:35.618 --> 19:38.482
Education really feels transactional.

19:38.502 --> 19:42.066
It's kind of a one way thing of like, hey, you need to know this, you need to do this.

19:42.206 --> 19:47.853
There's not a lot of space for people to ask questions and then have someone walk alongside them in the process.

19:47.873 --> 19:52.318
And that's what I love of how we disciple our students is that we stay alongside them.

19:52.919 --> 20:00.248
And that is a true formational practice that extends not only into our kids and students programs, but well into adulthood as well.

20:00.869 --> 20:05.074
And so I would say, if you're listening,

20:05.378 --> 20:13.888
You've maybe heard the message or maybe you didn't, but you feel this sense of retreat instead of wrestling in your life.

20:14.369 --> 20:18.514
I would encourage you to engage and take a small step this week.

20:18.734 --> 20:19.856
I don't know what that looks like for you.

20:19.976 --> 20:21.918
Maybe you'll consider serving.

20:22.339 --> 20:25.542
Maybe you'll put an inquiry forward and get to know our students a bit more.

20:25.643 --> 20:28.466
I mean, there's plenty of places to serve in our student programs, right?

20:28.866 --> 20:33.632
Or maybe you'll just reach out to one of our staff members and grab coffee, whatever that looks like.

20:34.373 --> 20:37.618
I just hope that you continue to wrestle with whatever's going on in your life.

20:37.798 --> 20:41.042
And so we're only in week two of this series.

20:41.242 --> 20:49.673
